Here is a sample of the types of things you'll read there:<br>
<br>
Dec. 30, 2002<br>
<br>
Monday<br>
<br>
Saw The Lord Of The Rings: The Two Towers for the fourth time today. It really is a very good flick.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm not one of these rabid fanboys that makes the LOTR flicks sound like they are the best movies ever made. No I'm well aware of many flaws in them, both from an adaptation of great literature and from a perfectionist filmmaker's standpoint. But even with the flaws they are very good flicks. Easily fitting into my top 10 movies of all time.<br>
<br>
But for me today the real story behind The Two Towers became more evident. Sure at their core the books and the films are about good versus evil. But what makes The Two Towers an extremely touching film is in how the characters are faced with that defining moment, the question of what will you do when all around you threatens that which you hold most dear?<br>
<br>
And in this film the answers from the characters are as realistic as one would expect from anyone in those types of troubled times. Let's look at them:<br>
<br>
The Hobbits: Frodo and Sam are closer to Hell than any sane being would ever dream of getting. Their quest is to take them directly into the heart of hell itself. They are faced with the reality that everything good in Middle Earth is depending on their success. Yet the weight of this burden is heavy, causing more pain with every step. As their journey becomes more difficult, so too become the pressures of triumphing. Frodo, torn between his comfortable existence of his past and the arduous journey ahead nearly gives in to the evil in the end. But it is through love, the love of his best friend that he is pulled out of darkness and back into light. Sam represents those of us who have suffered along side our loved ones. Offering them our own energy and strength when their own has gone. And it is through this act of compassion that Frodo finds his strength to forge ahead. I really relate to Samwise Gamgee. His character reminds me very much of who my sisters and I have tried to be for our Mother these past months as she's faced her own demons and monsters.<br>
<br>
Theoden (King of Rohan): After dealing with the deceit of friends and allies, Theoden is disheartened. His first impulse is to run from the darkness, to hide and believe that in hiding all will be well. But it is folly. Hiding only allows our fears to grow and our enemies and challenges to become more overwhelming. In the end Theoden, facing what may be his final moments, rediscovers that life is worth fighting for. That hiding away from adversity is never the answer. He recomposes himself and rides forth to meet his enemies head on. Knowing that he may not prevail, but in the fighting he might make his life stand for something.<br>
<br>
I could go on. But I'm tired. Perhaps, I'll write more tomorrow. Or I might not.<br>
<br>
After all, tomorrow's the dawn of a New Year, and with it comes new challenges and new dreams. Perhaps I'll wait and see what my new challenges will be first, and then share them with you...<br>
<br>
Until then!<br>
<br>
